Acts_As_Subscribable
======================================================
Allows one model to subscribe to another model's output
Create a migration that looks like this:

Acts as subscribable allows you to extend a model to afford other models to subscribe to another model. Acts_as_subcribable allows two types of 
subscriptions.
  1. Total Subscription - the subscriber gets an instance reference to the entire model for which it subscribes
  2. Partial Subscription - the model which accepts subscribers can choose to only expose a portion of their data to the model with subscribes.
  
The subscribable module transparently handles the implicit joins between the two models.



Example Usage - Total Subscription
======================================================
In this example the feed model returns a reference to the entire instance.

class user
  acts_as_subscribable :subscribe_to=>["Feed"]
end

class Feeds
  acts_as_subscribable 
end



Example Usage - Partial Subscription
======================================================
In this example, the feed model only returns one variable to the subscribers

class user
  acts_as_subscribable :subscribe_to=>[:Feed]
end

class Feeds
  acts_as_subscribable do
    feed_url #return only one variable
  end
end
  
  

Install
=======================================================
To install create this migration.

class AddFeedsAndSubscriptions < ActiveRecord::Migration
  def self.up
    create_table :subscriptions do |t|
      t.column :subscriber_id     , :integer
      t.column :subscription_id   , :integer
      t.column :subscribable_type , :string
    end
    
    create_table :feeds do |t|
      t.column :url  , :string
      t.column :name , :string
    end
  end

  def self.down
    drop_table :subscriptions
    drop_table :feeds
  end
end


